\f0\fs24 \cf0 Methods for detecting co-evolution at the protein level often mine phylogenetic trees that have been built for many protein families using entire protein sequences\super 20,21\nosupersub .
\b  
\b0 The co-evolution between interacting species, such as parasite\'96host, predator\'96prey and symbionts and their hosts, is in many cases manifested as a similarity of the phylogenetic trees of these co-evolving species. Likewise, molecular co-evolution caused by physical or functional protein interactions frequently results in similarities of the corresponding protein family trees. Consequently, approaches based on protein family tree similarity can successfully identify interaction partners for a given protein, such as ligand\'96receptor pairs\super 21,22\nosupersub .\
\pard\pardeftab708\ri-198\sl360\slmult1\sa20

