\b0 \cf0 In this Review, we present the most prominent computational methods based on co-evolution (Fig. 1). We progress through methods analyzing pairs, and then groups, of co-evolving residues, through to methods at the whole-protein level, describing the biological problems to which they have been applied, and briefly explaining the concepts and algorithms behind them. Key technical details (including the underlying algorithms) that differentiate the methods are described in Supplementary information S1\'96S4 (boxes), and examples of the connection between computational and experimental approaches are given in Boxes 1-3. For a summary of practical information about these computational methods and tools see Table 1. Finally, we discuss the problems related to the interpretation of the results in evolutionary terms, and present what, in our opinion, will be the most promising future developments.\
